# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1900-detroit-tigers-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The **1887 Detroit Wolverines season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The team won the 1887 National League pennant, then defeated the St.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The season was the team's seventh since it entered the National League in 1881.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] It was the first World Series championship for the Detroit Wolverines and the City of Detroit.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] On March 13, after training in Macon, Georgia‚ the Wolverines began a six-week exhibition tour through the South and Midwest.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Catching duties were divided between **Charlie Ganzel** (51 games at catcher) and **Charlie Bennett** (45 games at catcher).
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Both were good defensive catchers, though neither hit particularly well.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Bennett had a better fielding percentage than Ganzel (.951 to .913), but Ganzel was stronger in range factor (6.78 to 5.64) and fielding runs (9 to 2).
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Bennett's career in baseball ended when he lost both his legs in a train accident.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] When the Detroit Tigers opened their new ballpark in 1896, they named it Bennett Park in his honor.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] It remained Bennett Park until 1912, when the newly built stadium on the same site was named Navin Field.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] First baseman **Dan Brouthers** was the first of four future Hall of Famers to play for the 1887 Wolverines.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Brouthers won five batting titles and seven slugging titles, and his career batting average of .342 is the 9th highest in major league history.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Brouthers was a key to the Wolverines offensive output in 1887 as he led the National League in runs (153), doubles (36), extra base hits (68), on-base percentage (.426), times on base (246), and OPS (.988).
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] He was also among the league leaders with a .338 batting average (3rd in the NL), .562 slugging percentage (2nd in the NL), 20 triples, 12 home runs (5th in the NL), 101 RBIs (4th in the NL), 71 walks (4th in the NL), and an at-bat-to-strikeout ratio of 55.6 (2nd in NL).
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The second baseman duties were split between **Fred Dunlap** and **Hardy Richardson**.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Dunlap played 65 games at second base but missed two months due to an injury.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] As a result, Richardson played 64 games at second base in addition to 58 games as the left fielder.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Richardson was a big contributor to the 1887 Wolverines, as he hit for a .327 average with 51 extra base hits, 131 runs scored, 178 hits and 94 RBIs.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Richardson was also a good fielder both at second base and in left field.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Third baseman **Deacon White** was also part of "The Big Four" acquired from Buffalo before the 1886 season, and is the second of four future Hall-of-Famers on the team.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] White won two batting crowns earlier in his career but was 39 years old in 1887.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] He still hit for a .303 batting average and had 11 triples, 75 RBIs and 20 stolen bases.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] White was a nonsmoking, Bible-toting, church-going deacon.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] According to Lee Allen in *The National League Story* (1961), White was one of the last people to believe that the earth is flat.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Right fielder **Sam Thompson**, known as "Big Sam," was the third future Hall of Famer on the 1887 Detroit team.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Thompson was in his prime in 1887 and had a tremendous year.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] He was the National League batting champion with a .372 average, and he also led the league in slugging percentage (.571), hits (203), total bases (311), triples (23), RBIs (166), and runs created (127).
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] His 1887 total of 166 RBIs stood as a major league record for 40 years until Lou Gehrig broke it in 1927.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] 2 on the all-time home run list at the time of his retirement.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Center fielder **Ned Hanlon** was the fourth future Hall of Famer on the 1887 Detroit team.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Though inducted into the Hall of Fame based on his later performance as a manager, Hanlon was a good fielding center fielder who had tremendous speed and range.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] In 1887, he stole 69 bases for the Wolverines.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] He also hit .291 with seven stolen bases and 4 RBIs in the 1887 World Series.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The left fielder duties were split between second baseman/outfielder **Hardy Richardson**, and pitcher/outfielder **Larry Twitchell**.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] In addition to pitching 15 games for the Wolverines, Twitchell played 44 games in left field and 9 games in center field.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Twitchell had a .333 batting average and collected 51 RBIs in just 264 at bats.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] In his 15 games as a pitcher, Twitchell had a record of 11–1.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The Wolverines' #1 pitcher in 1887 was **Charlie Getzien**.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Getzien had a record of 29–13 for the 1887 team.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Getzien started 42 games, pitched 41 complete games, and had an ERA of 3.73.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] He was among the league leaders in wins, win percentage (.690), inning pitched (366.2), and strikeouts (135).
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] He was also first in the league with 24 home runs allowed.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] In the 1887 World Series, Getzien had a record of 4–2 with a 2.48 ERA.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Baldwin played four seasons with the Wolverines.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] In 1886, Baldwin had a record of 42–13 (the most wins ever by a Detroit pitcher) with a 2.24 ERA in 487 innings pitched, striking out 323 of 1936 batters faced.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Baldwin also completed 55 of 56 games, seven of which were shutouts.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] In 1887, Baldwin's appearances were reduced from 56 games to 24, and from 487 innings to 211.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] He won only 13 games in the regular season for the 1887 Wolverines, but in World Series play, Baldwin pitched 5 complete games for a 4–1 record and a 1.50 ERA.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The Wolverines' #3 pitcher was **George Edward "Stump" Weidman**.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Weidman led the National League with a 1.80 ERA for Detroit in 1881.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] In 1887, Weidman returned to the Wolverines, where he went 13–7.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] By late July, Weidman fell out of favor with manager William Watkins who considered Weidman to be a malcontent.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The Wolverines sold Weidman to the New York Metropolitans on August 5, 1887.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The Wolverines #4 pitcher was **Pete Conway**.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Despite his 8–9 record in 1887, Conway had the lowest ERA (2.90) among the Detroit starters.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The 1887 Wolverines finished the season with a record of 79–45.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] They outscored their opponents by more than 250 runs—969 to 714.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] They also led the National League in team batting average, runs scored and slugging.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Louis Browns in the 1887 World Series, 10 games to 5.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] After the Wolverines won the National League pennant, owner Fred Stearns challenged the American Association champion St.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The Wolverines and the Browns would play "a series of contests for supremacy" of the baseball world.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] This early "world series" consisted of fifteen games – played in Pittsburgh, Brooklyn, New York, Philadelphia, Boston, Washington, Baltimore and Chicago, as well as Detroit and St.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The Wolverines claimed their eighth victory – and thus the championship – in the eleventh game.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1894-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1894 throughout the world.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] The **1900 Detroit Tigers season** was the Tigers' first in the American League, which received recognition as a major league one year later in 1901.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers finished in fourth place out of eight teams with a record of 71–67, 12+1⁄2 games behind Charles Comiskey's Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit's home games were played at Bennett Park.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Outfielder Dick Harley led the team with a .325 batting average, 77 runs scored, and 47 stolen bases.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Sport McAllister led in slugging percentage (.383), and Frank Dillon led in extra-base hits (30).
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Roscoe Miller led the team with a 19–9 win-loss record for a .679 win percentage.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Jack Cronin led in innings pitched (372) and strikeouts (121).
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Burns and George Stallings had spent large sums of money for "releases of star players" and had paid "major league salaries" to the majority of the players.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The **1900 major league baseball season** began on April 19, 1900.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 14, with the Brooklyn Superbas as the regular season champion of the National League.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The Superbas and runner-up Pittsburgh Pirates competed in the *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup, a precursor to the current World Series, over four days, with Game 1 on October 15 and ended with Game 4 on October 18.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The Superbas defeated the Pirates in the best-of-five series in four games.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The 1900 season saw the return of a postseason championship series (albeit as a one-off), the *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup, following the end of the Temple Cup in 1897.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The 1900 season saw the aftermath of the National League contracting from 12 to 8 teams, eliminating the Baltimore Orioles, Cleveland Spiders, Louisville Colonels, and Washington Senators.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The elimination of major-league baseball from these cities prompted the minor league American League to declare themselves as a major league the following year.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The 1900 schedule consisted of 140 games for the eight teams of the National League.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams in the league.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] This format had previously been used by the National League during their 1888–1891 seasons.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] This format would last until 1904, which saw an increase of games played.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 19 featuring all eight teams.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season on October 14.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup, a precursor to the current World Series, took place between October 15 and October 18.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] 15 tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The **1901 Detroit Tigers season** was the Tigers' 2nd season in Major League Baseball.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The team was a charter member of the American League, which was originally formed as the minor-league Western League, of which it had also been a charter member.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers finished in third place with a record or 74–61, 8+1⁄2 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Most of Detroit's home games were played at Bennett Park, with Sunday games played at Burns Park due to Detroit's blue laws.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Roscoe Miller (23–13) led the team in wins and was the Tigers' first 20-game winner.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] His performance headlined a strong pitching staff that had the third lowest ERA (3.30) in the American League.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Joe Yeager had an ERA of 2.61, for the second best Adjusted ERA+ in the AL, behind Cy Young.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The offense was not as strong however, scoring 741 runs – fifth among the eight teams in the league.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The team's best hitters were shortstop Kid Elberfeld (.308 average) and center fielder Jimmy Barrett (.293 average; 110 runs).
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers had played their games at Bennett Park since 1896, but the graduation to a major league meant that there would now be games scheduled on Sundays, which was forbidden by Detroit's blue laws.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] In order to avoid running afoul of this stricture, owner James D.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Burns built a ballpark on his own property in Springwells Township, Michigan just outside the Detroit city limits.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Named Burns Park, the Tigers would play their Sunday home games there for the 1901 and 1902 seasons.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] During the 1901 season, Detroit attracted 259,430 fans at home and 238,100 on the road, for a total of 447,428.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit ranked third behind Chicago and Boston in overall attendance.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] 1902 was the second year for the **Detroit Tigers** in the newly formed American League.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished in seventh place with a record of 58–77 (.385), 30½ games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The 1902 Tigers were outscored by their opponents 657 runs to 566.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The team's attendance at Bennett Park was 189,469, sixth out of the eight teams in the AL.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit's blue laws prevented the Tigers from playing baseball at Bennett Park on Sundays.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] As a result, the Tigers played their Sunday home games for the season at Burns Park; a stadium constructed by owner James D.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1903-detroit-tigers-season] 1903 was the third year for the **Detroit Tigers** in the still-new American League.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1903-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished in fifth place with a record or 65–71 (.478), 25 games behind the Boston Americans.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1903-detroit-tigers-season] The 1903 Tigers outscored their opponents 567 to 539.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1903-detroit-tigers-season] The team's attendance at Bennett Park was 224,523, sixth out of the eight teams in the AL.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] 1904 was the fourth year for the **Detroit Tigers** in the American League.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished in seventh place with a record of 62–90 (.408), 32 games behind the Boston Americans.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] They played ten tie games, which is the major league record.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] The 1904 Tigers were outscored by their opponents 627 to 505.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] The team's attendance at Bennett Park was 177,796, seventh out of the eight teams in the AL.
[src:1900-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] In the year before Ty Cobb's arrival, pitcher George Mullin had a higher batting average than any of the team's regulars at .290.
